description: Today, we're covering the true scary story and unsolved mystery of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon. On April 1st, 2014, Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon disappeared without a trace into the jungle of Panama, remaining missing for only a couple of weeks. It wasn't long before locals began to stumble upon strange clues in the area they vanished, including a camera containing hundreds of disturbing photos that can't be explained. The investigation began. Detectives have combed over every single creepy photo searching for any possible clues or evidence to no avail. Although Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon have been found, no one can explain their scary disappearance to this day. Their missing persons case was utterly shocking and is still unexplained. Will this case ever be solved? What happened to the girls in the jungle, and who was snapping hundreds of photos DAYS after they disappeared? Today, we're giving our analysis of this creepy case and true story. Join us for a true crime storytime covering the unsolved mystery of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon.

The bra puzzle is the easiest:
A bra is a miserable thing to wear on a hot humid hike. They took them off for comfort and stuck them in the shared back pack. There was no one around to see anything, just two women. I remove mine as soon as I'm out of sight on a trail, on a long car ride....just anywhere it isn't necessary, most women ditch a bra anywhere they can get away with it, but especially in heat and humidity. They only used one back pack to take turns carrying it, since they didn't intend to be gone long. The orbs in the photos are just reflections on moisture droplets in the air. I've captured those in photos on a rainy or muggy night. I'm guessing here- but they probably took those 130+ photos that night because they heard someone or something nearby and they tried to signal help (or scare it away) with the flash. They were being very resourceful.

comments.text:
My beat friend served a 2 year church mission in the remote Panama areas as a service mission doing service for the native people. Church missionaries never carry cash and usually dont have any at all, they mind their own business and very giving and loving kids 19-26 years old. My best friend after his mission told me all about his 2 years . As a church missionary he was robbed, held at knives point 12 TIMES in 22 months in 5 different areas he served in. He said the thieves knew their routes home and usually waited until they were in a remote stretch of land , then would walk them off the road or trail into the jungle and rob them.  He said half those times the robbers were very agressive and threatened them saying he should kill them so they dont speak and 2 times they were told , if you go to the police , nothing will happen except they will tell me you did. Several indicating the police are on their sides.  They did report every case they felt they were in danger and not once were the police cooperative, never got back to them and absolutely no help. He said Panama was an extremely dangerous place and the church he belongs too about a decade ago pulled ALL their missionaries out of Panama for safety concerns. 
I mention this because a report I saw on this case said the police and locals avidly searched for these girls and it seems to infer the locals wouldnt hurt 2 beautiful young scantily dressed (according to locals, we see the pictures their in shorts tank tops and swim suits which to locals could be considered that)  the church hd also NEVER allowed female missionaries to go to panama after the early 1990s becasue of concern for their safety as 21 year old females, Ive never heard of the church allowing men but not girls so soenthing happened on several occasions to pull all females out for good.  These examples and concerns paint a very dangerous place for foreigners who are often seen as easy targets becasue theyre homes are thousands of miles away.  Sexual assault/rape are common among locals but authorities do nothing so to me it seems obvious these two pretty Caucasian foreigners were noticed by a local and followed or ran into them on the trail. Id guess SA was involved where the photo of a bloody head of one of the girls was on the camera.  I hadnt heard they hd a solar charger , the other documentary said they were trying to conserve the phones battery becasue they were lost and it died days after disappearing. A solar charger obviously eliminates a worry about phone dying or the possibility and makes sense that two extremely educated girls traveling the world performing service in a 3rd world country would bring a solar powered battery bank so I buy that.  The clean backpack showing up missing most items indicates someone robbed them or took things after kidnapping or murdering them washing the backpack before placing it in the open where it would be found.  After assaulting them a local would know the jungle wildlife would take care of the bodies if they did already dismember. The shoe and Foote SO far from the trail they were taking tells me they were walked far from that trail knowing people would search the trail. The police according to the parents said they were searching but ended up feeling like they didnt care and didnt believe they had searched like stated with investigators rarely returning calls or helping once the parents arrived.  
Its obvious to me with Panamas history of late they were murdered and I feel angry for the parents hearing true crime channels and documentaries pushing that the girls were just young and naive and got lost sucoming to the elements. None of the facts make sense to that suggestion. The phone attempted calls, pictures and the mystery deleted photo deleted AFTER their disappearance, the bloody head, the photos of nothing , a foggy sky wierd angles of jungle which would be someone not familiar with cameras pushing buttons , the girls were extremely smart and independent not stupid. And the media pushing a false idea of the local police and not ever mentioning the insane crime rate, murder rates and rapes in Panama painting it as a safe place for 2 young girls and locals as angels and police as eager to find these girls. Given the facts and recent history its quite clear what happened we just dont know the details. When people push that incorrect narrative it ruins the case becasue parents loose support because false infromation is spread and it demeans the victims and hurts the parents who know their daughters better.  I believe the parents words on the authorities and locals and my best friend and the church over Panamanian police mere words over the phone. If the media had spoke the truth about Panamas dark recent past and the United States governent suggesting Americans dont travel to panama tells me its not safe for 2 pretty young girls . Im a single dad of 3 amazing daughters that are my life and Id be asking their travel plans and researching the places their going dissuading any remotely unsafe places for young girls. The FBI suggests young American females travel with adult chaperons when traveling outside the US becasue of human /sex trafficking of foreigners globally from Europe, Asia , Middle East , Taiwan, Phillipines, South America etc. I understand girls wanting to be independent but a dangerous country for locals and especially foreign tourists as a parent put your foot down or at least try to convey with facts the danger. comments.text: Ive watched a few videos on this case and one other thing I found odd was that there were a few people who had reported seeing the girls leave/make it out of the trail, but for some reason the police didn't follow these leads and wrote them off as mistaken identity. I think there are a lot of things that point to foul play, but Kris's bones being chemically bleached and Lisanne's foot being cut off with a clean cut are the main pieces of evidence that don't line up to the authorities story. Authorities eventually wrote off the crime as the girls being lost and dying of natural causes, specifically claiming that they believed the girls fell off a cliff into a body of water. And that the water carried their remains all over the trail. However, their bones had no scratches, dents, cuts, chips, or any damage that would show their bones being carried. Kris's bones were found to have been missing tendons that would take years to decompose. Her bones were completely clean and bleached. If animals had found their bones and eaten what ever was on them, there would be bite marks or some type of remittance to show this. I always found the pictures taken at night very unsettling because we will never know who took those photos. Specifically the one picture of the back of Kris's hair/head. For someone who was walking around in the jungle for days, her hair looks completely clean and kept. The angle is very odd and either looks like she is lifting her hair up from underneath or that she is laying on the floor. As creepy as it is to say, she may not even be alive in that photo. I feel like those photos have something more behind them. Some have said that they believed they were using the flash to see their way, but this doesn't make sense. Some of the pictures look like they are taken near a cliff,  and some don't make sense.  Why would they be concerned about deleting a photo? Why did Kris continue to enter the pin to her own phone wrong several times? Why did their taxi driver take it upon himself to go to the home they were staying in, stay in their room for 30 minutes unattended, and only let the police know hours after starting his own search for them? comments.text:
They reached the summit an hour ahead of what they had planned and decided to go looking for waterfalls, though they had been advised not to. (They both had extensive search histories concerning the location of said waterfalls in the week leading up to their disappearance, but assured those who warned them not to look for them that they wouldn't... but they did end up with around two extra hours they weren't expecting to have by reaching the summit early...) The gullies they photographed themselves in were not all along their original path and have since been identified. As has the dirt trail they were on a week later. What most likely happened was that they realized they weren't going to be able ro make it back to the summit (and thus the only path back to town) before it got dark  and were going to have to spend the night on the mountain. In that gully area, the only cleared ground suitable for setting up any sort of makeshift camp would be one of the gullies themselves. They made their first attempts to contact help around an hour before dark which makes sense. The temperature was in the mid to upper 50's at night, and they were in shorts and tee shirts, so they would have wanted shelter. The debris formations they took pictures of themselves in front of would have seemed ideal for that. Such gullies are dangerous (especially before the rainy season is fully under way) since blockages can form and hold back water, leading to a very strong surge with debris down the mountain when the blockage gives. It likely rained that night, and they got hit by such a surge with nowhere to go inside the debris tunnel they were in. I've seen such surges, and they would definitely have been injured to some degree and washed along for a bit. Had one or both been carried to where the incline steepened, it would have led to significant injuries and no viable way back up.

They would have had to travel down the gully, which would have taken them to the river. There, they would have had water, but nowhere to really go (especially if one or more were injured) and would likely have decided to wait and hope a boat would go by (highly unlikely), or searchers would find them. You can go quite a while without food, but after about a week, you'd be pretty desperate. The dirt path they were on in their week later photos has since been identified via drone, and when you see it, things start to make sense. It ran along a gully and from the bottom likely looked like it went all the way up. It didn't. About halfway up, it essentially ran into a wall of dense foliage with nowhere to go. That would have been the last of their energy and the point at which at least one was likely to more or less give up. They probably went back down the mountain to their water source to wait for help, one died, and the other was too weak to make it for much longer. The only way back up would have been a gully, and by then, there was likely a good bit of water flowing down, so the survivor would have had no options. Nature took care of things from there.

The concerned looks on their faces in some of the gully photos were likely the result of their realizing they weren't going to get back in time but might as well take the pictures since that's what got them into the mess in the first place. While the night photos were likely just them using the flash as a flashlight. The head photo makes sense if you have an injured half starved person going up an incline with the person behind them taking periodic pictures to see where they were going. A stumble and fall would bring the person behind down as well, and a photo could easily have been snapped in the process. The photos aimed upwards were probably an attempt to signal a drug plane heard but not seen (as they run without lights) which regularly fly over that area at night. (Somewhere down there, there's probably such a pilot who saw those flashes but can't say anything about it because then they would have to explain why they were flying over that area at night with no flight plan registered anywhere.)

The physical evidence all makes sense as remains and items will get washed into the river during the rainy season. Also, the people in the village were not informed of the missing hikers until quite a while afterward and their stories as to where the evidence was found and it's initial condition were different depending on which villager was asked. They had probably already found the stuff, cleaned it, and were using some of it when they found out, and just threw it all back together to turn it in. The phones and camera were damaged and not in working condition with quite a bit of garbled data on them. The investigators were simply able to retrieve some of the data from them. The oddities of missing photos etc. could easily be explained by that. The "famous" missing photo had a registry entry but no trace of the actual image file. That can happen from a glitch. The investigators merely said that the only way it could have manually been removed was via PC, not that it had been removed so. Anyone smart enough to remove the image file would have purged the registry entry as well and attempted to adjust the numbering to completely cover it... or just destroyed the camera (and phones) to make sure there was no evidence to begin with. The foot in the shoe is perfectly natural when it comes to human remains. Shoes slow the decomp process down which leads to the feet eventually falling off. Shoes are somewhat buoyant, so if they end up in the water, they'll travel along. The "sun bleached" bones were most likely not truly or fully sun bleached. A couple of species of the last stage decomp beetles in the area excrete phosphates as they do their work. Such phosphates easily and quickly leech into the bone and turn it very white (they even have a slight glow in the dark for a bit after prolonged exposure to sunlight.)

I think that covers most of the "mystery."

In a video, the mother of Kriss who came on the trail explains that she is absolutely sure that if one of the girls had been injured, they would have stayed on the trail and waited. The problem actually is that he There was no injury or other, only from being trapped by the time and the arrival of night, and also from not having warned anyone.

So they get lost. And the second catastrophe arrives, no one knows where they went or more precisely, no one knows that they continued beyond the Mirador, towards the North on the path. So by the time we organize the research, a lot of time will pass. And we will have to wait until April 6 for research to be done on the other side of the Mirador. That is to say that the girls got lost, that they continued to move during these 6 days, if only to try to find a place with a little network. Fear, anxiety, stress, exhaustion...etc. When the search begins beyond the Mirador, the girls are already in a bad state in my opinion.

Hello. I have been following this case for a long time. Here's just some information:

The night time pictures are all of the same patch of sky. It's actually possible to overlap them, to show that someone was on the ground, pointing the camera up, and took a bunch of pictures of the exact same area. I personally believe the girl holding the camera fell off a cliff, down an escarpment, into a wadi, or whatever other earth term there is for saying "fell down, got hurt, steep drop" they weren't using the flash to find their way, it was one girl trying to signal where she was to the other girl.

The missing picture? I think that happened during the fall. It's possible that the jolting of the camera caused it to go off, but it's battery could have gotten rattled at the same time, creating and error at the same time as the picture was taken. This would cause it to be 'deleted' and still counting as being there, at the same time.

I think they both were very smart. They must have used a watch to help them figure out when to turn on their phones. I'm guessing one of them had a digital watch set to go off at like, 10am every day. They didn't waste the batteries, they kept to a schedule. I think they both did eventually die near the river, cause their body parts were found downstream.

comments.text:
On every true crime video, it seems there's someone who comments how out of the many, many true crime cases they've watched, THAT one is the that sticks with them the most. This is that case for me--well, tied with the whole Turtle Island Thailand gang-corruption-coverup murders haha. 

Any theory on this case (or derivative) get be picked apart so it's frustrating. Some things start to make sense in your mind, it's all clicking together, and then you go "but wait, what about the ___ " So yeah the only thing i'm certain of is that i'm not certain. I do notice however, that people who support the theory that they just got lost (whether coupled with an animal attack, a fall of a cliff, effects of dehydration etc.) don't seem able or willing to refute arguments for the (a) foul play theory. 

Even to believe they were kidnapped by a gang would open up so many more questions that have left people scratching their heads. But I tend to lean towards some form of the foul play theory, and here why.

Points that contradict the theory that they just got lost:

1) the backpack -- it was found 70 days after the girls' disappearance, beside a river bank 15 km away from the pianista trail. The lady who found it said she was at the same spot the day before but didn't see any backpack there. The backpack was NOT wet -- it was in pristine condition and the items inside were dry and appeared untouched. The phones and digital camera were in there, so it becomes difficult to see how the girls could've been the ones taking the pictures and calling emergency services in the jungle for 11 days, and yet the backpack doesn't get wet or dirty, and somehow makes a long journey on its own without getting wet. 

2) Lisanne's severed left foot was found in her hiking boot, and the cut was clean -- This disproves any animal attack theory and shows a human being cut off her foot. Unless Pokemon are real and a Scyther jumped out and cut her foot off, then it was a human. It can't be argued that an animal could have done that, plus the boot was clean and still tied to her foot, with no sign of scratches or claw marks

Honestly, I don't see how anyone can believe they just got lost given the above 2 points. Ok let's tack on some more for goal differential :P

3) Pictures -- I'm hoping people have watched/read other things about this case, to gather more details. The daytime pictures and nighttime pictures tell completely different (albeit incomplete) stories. 

Timeline: they start their hike on April 1st. Yikes, I didn't even notice that was April Fool's, ugh. 

-> daytime pictures - The girls are smiling. These are the ones at the foot of the trail, along it and leading up to them reaching the peak where I wish they had been able to turn back. In the strange pictures of Kris beside the stream of water and crouched by the bushes, she's not smiling at all and some believe at this point they were either kidnapped or had run into another group and knew they were dangerous.

 These initial pictures were taken before 1:30-2:00pm, so that refutes the taxi driver saying he dropped them off at that time. Nope, he might've just misremembered but this notion that they started their hike at 2pm is simply false. MORE on that taxi driver in a bit ....

> nighttime pictures - After 2pm on April 1st, no one used the camera for 7 days. It just doesn't make sense, if they were alone and simply lost, to not have a SINGLE picture of them, or anything in the daytime for that matter. But then on April 8th, someone took more than 90 photos in less than 3 hours - those hours were between 1am-4am. This is where the "they just got lost" camp suggests that these photos were meant to light up the area so they could see their surroundings, perhaps signal an airplane or search party, or perhaps scare off an animal they (or rather just she, by this point) might have heard. I have to admit, whyy would kidnappers be out at 1-4am taking pictures though? Best chance to not be seen as they make it look like the girls took the pictures in the jungle? Oh, I dunno. But then again, WHY was there 0 camera activity for 7 days?

Then there's the deleted photo and this one's a mammoth. Keep in mind that pictures were taken on a digital camera, not their phones. A computer must be used to fully erase a photo, and the Canon company itself confirmed this. It makes a strong argument that the girls managed to get a picture of something or someone incriminating, and whoever kidnapped them (* cough Feliciano Gonzales) had to have deleted the picture. 

4) Phones -- alright so on the first day, April 1st, the first emergency call to 112 was placed just after 4:30pm. Then a call was placed to 911 but didn't get through. Then phones turned off for 14 hours. Again, why? If they were lost and had their phones, how do they both go 14 hours without having their phone on? 

In total, they made about 80 calls. On day 5 (April 5th) LIsanne's phone died. Kris's phone stayed on until day 11 but between April 7th-10th Kris's phone was off/had no activity. It was turned on again, for the last time, at 10:51am on April 11th. It was turned off exactly an hour later at 11:51am, and this was the end of any phone activity. 

On April 6th, there were several attempts to enter an incorrect code. There were dozens of attempts up until April 11th. The girls obviously would have exchanged pass codes so it's very unlikely that Lisanne would've been locked out of Kris's phone. Plus, they didn't need a pass code to make an emergency call so investigators concluded it was unlikely to have been Lisanne trying to enter the code. The girls hadn't called home or the place they were staying, or anything other than emergency services in those 11 days so that seemed a bit strange. Why "dozens" of attempts to enter a phone, unless it was kidnappers looking for photos or something before they plant the phones in the backpack and leave them by the river. 

5) Tour guide / gang members 
Oh I gotta wrap this up. No one's reading anyway but I can't sleep so let's write until the eyes get heavy haha. Okay but yeah, let's go over some of these characters.

Feliciano Gonzales - the tour guide
Internet sleuths like me believe he's our guy. He basically IS a red flag, everything that he does. The girls were supposed to meet with Feliciano but they didn't. So after the girls went missing, he went over to the place they were staying and was in the girls' room for 30 minutes. There wasn't a door key in the backpack that was found, which doesn't make sense. Then of course it's Feliciano who spotted the boot with Lisanne's severed foot in it, and other bones. 33 bones were discovered, one pair of jean shorts, and one shoe from each of the girls. Then there was a rolled up ball of human skin. Then you look at Feliciano's tripadvisor reviews online and the one where he threatens a woman with a machete sticks out. Machete, clean cut above the ankle, hmm. OH, and then the suspicious deaths. Over 10 people connected to the case have died, including 4 member of the Los gang. The one gang member who survived? Henri Elizas Gonzales, Feliciano's son. Alright. 

Taxi driver -- named Leonardo Gonzales -- drove the girls to la pianista, told police he saw a pickup truck near where he dropped the girls off. He was found dead in a river, 7 months after the girls' disappearance.

Gang member 1 - Osman Velezuales (23 years old) - died April 4th (3 days after the girls' disappearance). 

2 - Juan Rivera Miranda (24)
3 - Jorge Murgas (23)
4 - Adonis Henriberto (23)

One was drowned in a shallow pool, one hit and run, and I forget the other. I'm tired, still need to look up another supposed suspect named Plineo Montenegro. 

But yeah, again no one will have read this but forgive the long rant, anyway. This case just has so many strange elements to it. I mean, the girls actually had a compass, a solar power bank, and a knife in their room. They obviously would've taken these if they planned to go on a long hike, which further makes me believe they were intercepted at some point on the trail. 

It just seems obvious that there was foul play involved. Foul play's a euphemism for what Lisanne and Kris went through, and I can't see any way they just got lost. Again they didn't pack much, they didn't take any daytime photos after the first 2 hours of their hike, the condition of the bone fragments, the knowledge of gang/police/government corruption in Panama, all of it. If they were lost, wouldn't they have tried to mark where they've been? It's dense jungle but even little pieces of clothing tied to a tree could be seen by people searching. What about trying to make SOS signs out of rocks or sticks?> Or at least make piles of random sticks and brush so you'll know you've been there before, and people searching can tell a human made those piles. 

I dunno, it just seems a bit disrespectful to the girls and their lives to believe they were foolish and got lost. Just think, if Lisanne or Kris was your daughter, would you be able to look at this case and accept that the girls must've just got lost? Evidence for them being lost pales in comparison to them being kidnapped, does it not?

Then again, I could be wrong :)

I dont think they were particularly lost or disposed of, just stuck being injured until they perished.

The backpack being found dry is much disputed, and apparently according to police and forensics is untrue, as the phones were reported to be specially dried. The missing photo (or potentially video) was likely a temporary camera error (probably after getting wet) which would explain them not even trying the camera again until the 8th in desperation.

The night photos were taken in a gully with some water that the girls found themselves in, with Kris likely completely incapacitated in that place by then, and Lisanne taking them in a daze trying to signal upwards to rescuers, while also accidentally snapping a pic of her friends hair next to her, as well as the outline of a side of her own face, all until the battery died. April 11th phone activity could have been an erroneous water-induced signal turn-on that is known to happen, considering there were no other actions on it afterwards, or a last ditch attempt of Lisanne to try getting any use of it before succumbing to the environment.

Lack of texts to family could be due to them likely not having a local SIM (or one at all), so no roaming. And thats not counting further reasons like due to insufficient credit, battery saving focused only on 911 calls, or just incomplete data accumulated. The piece of skin being Lisannes is also disputed, and was apparently examined to be of animal (cow) origin. The jean shorts were probably used as a pillow during the night and/or became irritating to wear; them being neatly folded instead of washing up is also likely erroneous reporting. And cleanly severed feet in shoes washing up is actually a common occurrence. Establishing Occams razor is not necessarily simple, but theres still not enough concrete evidence of foul play to beat it.

One things for sure though, regardless of where the thought on this case falls, the overall feeling starts with what were Dutch girls doing in the wildness of Panama either way? and ends with why were they keen for Panamanian wilderness instead of the beautiful capital of Panama City or other well-populated exotic cities in the Americas?

comments.text: Okay, bare with me. But this is my theory on what happened to these two poor young ladies. I believe something happened between 13:20 and 13:54. The contrast between the photos taken at this time show Kris pulling a silly face, sticking her tongue out and posing without care, to her displaying an awkward stance, with a serious expression, perhaps concerned. It looks like it went from having fun to not enjoying themselves at this point, between these 34 minutes. Could be that they were fed up of the walk, having gone further than planned and realised they were lost. They hadnt planned on a long hike, as they didnt have a large supply of drinking water, nor spare clothing if the weather changed. They seemed like smart girls with travelling experience, so I dont think they would have simply taken these chances without planning. Someone encountered them after the photos at 13:20. They took possession of the camera and led them deeper into the rain forest, snapping shots of Kris, forcing her to pose, and keeping Lisa out of view, either to create the illusion that Lisa was taking them as they continued their walk, or this was a strange form of torture. Maybe the stranger had offered to take photos but the girls became uncomfortable, the person became agitated. Because, following the photos at 13:54 when Kris doesnt seem to be smiling like she is in all the previous photos, and it being further past the trail than they had planned or been advised to go, thats when the photo which was deleted occurred. Perhaps the person taking the photo accidentally captured one of themselves, maybe even just their own finger which could have given away the evidence that the girls were not alone. Or somehow the girls had taken the camera back and taken a snap of this person. Maybe they were arguing with them, stating that they didnt want to be followed or joined any more by this person. Could be they didnt mind the company to begin with, not expecting the person to want to tag along for longer than a couple of minutes, or could be they felt obliged to be friendly to a local person but felt awkward. The stranger becomes offended, and with agitation he threatens them. One of the girls takes a photo of them. This aggravates the stranger, and they snatch the camera back and delete the pic. Maybe the girls tried to take the camera back and this person attacks them. It escalates. He hits Kris or uses a weapon. Maybe she is knocked unconscious. Or she is killed. He then does the same to Lisa. Maybe they were bound, sexually assaulted - no evidence of this, but its a possibility - and killed. Perhaps, during the time in which they are being followed or led away, the girls tried calling the emergency services to no avail. By the time the person caught up with them, or realised they had been making calls, these calls stopped, the phones being taken from them. Or they were faked by the third party themselves. After the girls were killed, I believe their bodies were taken away. This leads to the theory that there would have been more than one attacker to carry the bodies and belongings away. Whatever the reason, whether needing to get rid of evidence following an opportunist murder, or for some satanic ritual including potential cannibalism, or an act of organ trade, the bodies were then disposed of: skinned (perhaps consumed by human or animal assistance), dismembered, bones shattered into smaller pieces. The bones were bleached, perhaps to remove evidence, perhaps out of some psychopathic act of cherishing their trophy kill. This explains the severed foot (by machete, common use in the Panamanian jungle), the rolled up skin, the bleached pelvis bone, the other thirty or so bone particles discovered over a stretch of land. These were all saved and deliberately placed further from where the girls were killed, including the backpack which was dry and in perfect condition, bras neatly stacked inside, having been removed when the women were possibly assaulted, and in any case when killed, neither of which would have occurred if the backpack was left in the rain forest for as many weeks as it was suggested - since the time of the girls coming into trouble and making calls; nor would the body parts have naturally decomposed in a natural environment the way they did if left in the jungle - they were preserved, and saved for a later moment to be discovered to confuse the officials and public. The perpetrator used the camera to take the confusing nighttime photos in sporadic succession days after the girls were killed, to suggest the girls were alive and had taken the themselves. I fail to believe these photos were taken by either girl - so many days had passed since the hike and emergency calls, and they had no water source, nor food, not to mention suffering with the heat and the heaving rain. Perhaps the hair was always saved and used in this pic to appear as though she is still in the jungle at this point. Hair doesnt die with the rest of the body when decomposing. Kriss phone was plugged in by whoever had possession of this in the following days after their kidnap/murder, desperately attempting to access the phone, either to delete photos in fear of there being any evidence, or for sheer curiosity, wanting to invade the girls private life more than they already had. Maybe someone knew they were heading into the forest and followed them, or let slip to another stranger of their whereabouts, such as the tour guide or taxi driver. Their items in the backpack such as the knife and compass which were missing were simply stolen by whomever took their belongings. It could be that the items were left when the girls were taken away and were later found/stolen by someone else, only to realise who it belonged to and returned them to the forest in fear of being accused of having involvement. Police did a poor job with solving the case either because: a) they were confused with all the events and lazily failed at tying it together, b) they dont want it solved due to the knowledge that a third party involvement of their nationality would create negative media coverage, affecting tourism which the community heavily relies on as a main source for income, or c) perhaps the police were even involved/aware of the specifics of the crime, if such a thing as organ trade or human trafficking were prevalent in the area. Terrible story, horrifies me and makes me so sad to know they were out there enjoying a holiday with their best friend, to end up the way they did. True horror story material. Awful. I just hope the girls had each other for longer than predicted or I can figure out, that they looked after each other as best they could - its horrible to know they loved each other and were in that situation together, maybe one having to see the other be killed, or each other be assaulted/killed. comments.text: Dude, my boyfriend and I LOVE this channel, but we have unanimously come to the conclusion that this is hocus pocus. Almost all of the "unusual" and "unexplainable" mysteries surrounding this case can reasonably be explained away by common happenings in missing hiker situations. For one thing, the friend that looks "worried" in some of the later photos, doesn't really look all that worried to me? Assuming for argument's sake that she is boasting a less-than-happy expression, that is likely because the photos are candid (which they definitely appear to be) and I don't know many people that can naturally flash an extravagant smile, such as those shown in the earlier posed photos, while being candidly photo'd. Not only this, but she's likely a lot more worn down at this point in the hike. Secondly, while it's true that emergency calls can be made without unlocking a smartphone, once a person is dehydrated they are really very disoriented and it would not be surprising if they had forgotten this knowledge, assuming the phone did have that capability and they were aware of that capability in the first place (I was pretty ditzy at 21...). Not only would they have been dehydrated, but it would seem that the owner of the phone had either perished or was close to it, which would definitely panic the living friend--making it even more likely that they would behave erratically and not be in the right mindset to 1. Remember the pin code (if their dying/dead friend had given it to them before) 2. Recall that emergency phone services are available without unlocking the phone. Also, we have no idea what the person trying to unlock phone was actually trying to achieve--maybe it was something that did require the phone to be unlocked. There's really no telling what a severely dehydrated and panicked lost hiker is thinking. The photos in the dark are definitely either one of the girls flashing for help or lighting their way in the dark. Photos from a digital camera should be retrievable even if they were deleted from the camera, so idk why investigators didn't try to retrieve them if there are deleted photos as was stated. Maybe the photos were one girl taking a photo of their deceased friend for documentation, but were then deleted because the girl changed her mind about having such a gruesome thing documented? Serious speculation on my part there, but it really could have been anything that was deleted. As for the remains potentially indicating foul play... it would be very very VERY strange for a "killer" to hold the girls hostage until they literally died from natural causes. Like, all evidence points to them dying slowly, making multiple concerted attempts over a lengthy span of time to contact help to no avail. I have no idea what the motive would be for a kidnapper or murderer to just tag along with the girls until they died. Their remains showing little to no decomposition could very well be evidence of scavenging animals picking the corpses clean. Given the sheer biodiversity of Panama, there are likely many animals around to take care of that job. Of course, the forensics would have to show signs of this, so if they don't then  also any footprints left by animals would have been washed away after 70 days, though it is possible their remains washed into the river during a high water event and were carried downstream from the actual place of death anyway. Of course locals are going to say it's hard to get lost in that forest... they're locals! Not only that, but hikers go missing ALL THE TIME on well-marked and well-traveled trails. A fall or injury would exacerbate getting lost. I agree that some things are strange, like the clean cut to the leg if that is accurate. And the rolled up skin... though that one perplexes me as, surely investigators would have taken that to a lab for DNA testing? If another person rolled that skin up (or monkey or whatever) there would probably be some DNA trail. 70 days in a rainforest may have eliminated such data, though. The pristine backpack is pretty strange, but I'm betting the condition of the backpack is maybe exaggerated a little... bht still  The best explanation is the most likely one. I get making stories out to have dramatic or creepy spins for content, but this just sounds like a really sad story of two friends getting lost in the Rainforest and dying with some odd twists thrown in the middle
